Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.36,0:01:54.64,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(0,200)\c&H1C3C96&\3c&HDEF2DC&} {Warm }Welcome, {\c&H041911&}Matsumoto Sawako! {熱烈歡迎松本佐和子さん}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.47,0:01:57.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Is she really coming on that flight? {volume 2 page 35}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:57.86,0:02:01.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah... Greeting people at the airport is just not my thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:01.16,0:02:03.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Shouldn't have agreed to this job. {no clue what's this anmitsuippai, could be the nameplate she is holding, could be that she's literally taking sawako to eat anmitsu after this; also she says "didn't undertake" without "yokatta" but believing DeepL here; TLC}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.59,0:02:06.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you the Taihei Finance representative? {shouji could be "commercial affairs" so I think it means some company dealing with finances, tho can't be sure as none of the company names are in manga}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.16,0:02:07.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes...
Dialogue: 0,0:02:13.28,0:02:15.38,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm Matsumoto Sawako.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:18.18,0:02:20.43,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm so glad you decided to start your career at Taihei!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:20.43,0:02:22.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Leaving behind many of our male employees, {honestly, no clue what she means, must be "並み居る男子社員を差し置き" but I've no clue what's either ". to sit in a row; to be present (and lined up)" or "to leave as is; to let alone; to disregard"}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.26,0:02:26.78,Default,,0,0,0,,you now qualify as a super-elite, with a huge advantage \Nof graduating abroad from Harvard Business School!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.78,0:02:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,I've never met someone so amazing!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:29.35,0:02:32.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Not only that, you got a Master's degree \Nin Business Administration - MBA!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:32.36,0:02:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Not to mention the astounding success that the launch \Nof Hayate Motor Company's first factory in the U.S. had been! {unsure, "advance (into a new market, industry, etc.); expansion (into); launch (into); entering; making inroads (into)"}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.36,0:02:39.78,Default,,0,0,0,,I can't stress it enough how much I admire you!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.33,0:02:51.33,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder what happened, it's not even the rush hour yet. {lit: time to congest/for traffic}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.33,0:02:54.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Ma'am, these days, \Nthis part of the city{added} is constantly like that.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.52,0:02:56.42,Default,,0,0,0,,I see... It'll take a little longer than expected. {guess, last word}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.42,0:03:00.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Yukie, I feel like walking the rest of the way{ to the office/company} on feet. \NLet's get off here.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.60,0:03:14.37,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(0,1300)} Detroit, Michigan{ USA}. October 1980. {volume 1 p.3}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.41,0:03:14.89,Default,,0,0,0,,This year, the American automobile industry output {/production volume}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.89,0:03:19.14,Default,,0,0,0,,experienced a sharp decline, \Ncompared to last year's 11,480,000.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.14,0:03:21.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, the "number one in the world" position \Nwas yielded to Japan.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.99,0:03:24.60,Default,,0,0,0,,The U.S. had to content themselves with being number two. {to content oneself with; to be resigned to (one's fate); to be contented (satisfied) with (one's lot)}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:30.29,0:03:32.11,Default,,0,0,0,,We're boycotting the Japs!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.88,0:03:34.71,Default,,0,0,0,,That's right! We won't tolerate no dumping! {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dumping_(pricing_policy)}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.71,0:03:35.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactly!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.38,0:03:37.86,Default,,0,0,0,,The government must immediately \Nimpose import restrictions!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.86,0:03:40.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll take our jobs back by force!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.76,0:03:44.66,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a Japanese car!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:45.76,0:03:46.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Show 'em what we think of it! {tsubuse}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.51,0:03:49.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's flatten the Jap car!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.02,0:03:50.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Right, right!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:50.39,0:03:51.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's get it! {yacchimae}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.35,0:03:51.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Here I go!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.65,0:03:57.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Watch out! {abunaizo}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.33,0:04:10.33,Sign,,0,0,0,,Central Motor Company chairman, Hoffman {/Automobile Association セントラル自動車会長\Nホフマン}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.47,0:04:14.32,Default,,0,0,0,,It's me. Put me through to Washington.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.79,0:04:17.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Hoffman's play is pretty obvious. {見えすいた演出を}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.79,0:04:22.05,Sign,,0,0,0,,General Manager of the President's Office, Showa Motor Co., Ltd. {昭和自動車社長室長}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.79,0:04:22.05,Default,,0,0,100,,He is scheming to stir a commotion big enough \Nfor Washington to start feeling the pressure.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.05,0:04:27.05,Sign,,0,0,0,,CEO, Showa Motor Co., Ltd. {/president 昭和自動車社長}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:22.05,0:04:27.05,Default,,0,0,100,,Consequently, this pressure is projected on our government, \Nwho would eventually cave in to export self-restrictions{ that is his plan}.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.05,0:04:30.66,Default,,0,0,0,,And if it looks like we are restricting exports \Nof our own free will,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.66,0:04:34.59,Default,,0,0,0,,that would serve to deliver us \Nfrom any political or legal repercussions.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.49,0:04:41.63,Default,,0,0,0,,And once the restrictions are imposed, the foreign market \Nwould distinctly feel the shortage of Japanese cars.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:41.63,0:04:43.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Without a doubt, prices will also rise.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.78,0:04:46.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Naturally, it's what Hoffman is aiming for.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.24,0:04:49.31,Default,,0,0,0,,If the prices go up, the sales of the Japanese cars go down.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.31,0:04:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,In turn, Central Motor Company, currently on the skids, \Nwould be able to catch a breath.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:53.50,0:04:55.78,Default,,0,0,0,,So it's only a stopgap measure, after all.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.57,0:05:01.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Those guys are too busy\Nplaying their zaitech-like money games. {running about; making every effort (to do); busying oneself (with); being busily engaged (in); good offices; efforts ... money management technique; zaitech}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.30,0:05:04.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Meanwhile, their production facilities \Nare neglected and operate ancient tools.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.59,0:05:07.65,Default,,0,0,0,,If you compare the number of personnel \Nneeded to produce a single car,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:07.65,0:05:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the aggressive optimization had allowed us to reduce it \Nto less than one-third of what they need, and it's not over yet. {unsure what to make of to press forward; to forge ahead; to push on here}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.95,0:05:18.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Those fellows are spooked by every smallest trifle. \NIt's a problem. {honestly no clue who he means any why shouldn't they be scared of trifles so having to revert this, originally he says "are not easily intimidated"; TLC}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:18.40,0:05:21.48,Default,,0,0,0,,But a self-restriction inevitably entails \Na local production, right? {actually "on the spot/on scene/local" but this is more clear}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.48,0:05:25.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Correct. The workers' demand \Nof getting employed has to be met.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.45,0:05:28.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Until then, the unrest would only grow more rabid.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.45,0:05:33.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir, our rivals at Kostar Motors \Nare steadily ramping up their preparations. {not sure about the exact word, hope they don't bring it up again}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:33.06,0:05:37.21,Default,,0,0,0,,And the Hayate, following next, \Nhave already switched to local production this year. {no clue what's succeeding; following; trailing; next here, could be "our second rivals"? TLC}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.62,0:05:39.00,Default,,0,0,0,,For our company, too...
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.00,0:05:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, we're facing the same old problem as before, aren't we? {しかしうちは例の問題を抱えているからな but I have no clue what's exemplary problem so copying manga tl here}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.96,0:05:45.51,Default,,0,0,0,,What I mean is, just like we always do at times like this,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.51,0:05:47.98,Default,,0,0,0,,we should take a plunge for a decisive surgical action. {from manga, I take it they didnt understand what he means as well as they had "what I mean is, we're always having to perform a major surgery in mitsutomo company" - といっていつまでもこのままではここらで大手術をするべきです ; TLC}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.68,0:05:58.60,Sign,,0,0,0,,Business Headquarters Office {業務本部室}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.68,0:05:58.60,Default,,0,0,100,,The self-restrictions are finally places.\NThe government couldn't hold out any longer.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.60,0:06:01.67,Default,,0,0,0,,They set the next year's estimate \Nat only 1,680,000 cars produced?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.67,0:06:03.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that was a one-sided battle all along.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.55,0:06:05.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Anyway, I'll go report it to the department chief. { general manager; director-general}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.00,0:06:07.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Ouch...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.74,0:06:08.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you blind... {not sure what he means by "done/screwed arent you"}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:10.07,0:06:12.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Department chief! We have just received a telex...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.31,0:06:13.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Self-restrictions, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.74,0:06:18.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Just now, I've received a call \Nfrom the executive director of Hayate Motor Company.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.50,0:06:19.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, I see...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.79,0:06:24.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Matsumoto, at Hayate, they're extremely grateful \Nfor your mediation in arranging their local production.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.97,0:06:28.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh... But all I did was provided \Nsome superficial assistance on the spot. {lit: just helped}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.65,0:06:30.24,Default,,0,0,0,,You can be infinitely humble,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.24,0:06:33.39,Default,,0,0,0,,but Hayate consider your early prediction \Nof such a turn of events,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.39,0:06:36.10,Default,,0,0,0,,as well as your advice \Nof taking a plunge with local production, {to take the plunge; to decide; to embark on; to venture into; to launch out into}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.10,0:06:38.77,Default,,0,0,0,,a testimony to your extremely keen foresight.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.77,0:06:44.17,Default,,0,0,0,,It gave them no less than 2 or 3 years of advantage \Nover two other major companies - Showa and Kostar. {/went earlier}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.75,0:06:48.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, have you ever seen a woman studying abroad,\Nlet alone in Harvard Business school? {despite being a woman; woman as she is; (in a way that is) unbecoming to a woman; (in a way that is) uncharacteristic of a woman; in an unladylike way}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.15,0:06:51.28,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd wager their appreciation lies with this fact alone.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.28,0:06:53.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Manager, what is that "where have you seen a woman" talk?! {what did you mean by despite being a woman; woman as she is; (in a way that is) unbecoming to a woman; (in a way that is) uncharacteristic of a woman; in an unladylike way}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.74,0:06:54.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Yukie...
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.15,0:07:00.37,Default,,0,0,0,,At any rate, the said Showa Motor Co. \Nhad also made contact with us.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.37,0:07:01.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Eh? Showa did?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.88,0:07:04.42,Default,,0,0,0,,They'd like to hear a straightforward lecture from you, {frank; candid; outspoken; unreserved}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.42,0:07:07.92,Default,,0,0,0,,recounting all the difficulties Hayate had, \Nwhen opening a local production plant.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.92,0:07:12.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Which means Showa are also starting \Nto seriously consider the possibility of local production..?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.40,0:07:13.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Their intentions are unclear.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.76,0:07:15.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Mikawa and Matsumoto,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.31,0:07:19.18,Default,,0,0,0,,on the evening of Saturday, would you be able \Nto meet with their Manager of the President's Office?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.18,0:07:23.94,Default,,0,0,0,,Terribly sorry, but on Saturday, I'm tending \Nto some personal matters in Kyoto, therefore I can't. {unsure, this private could be anything else}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.94,0:07:26.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey! Goyo Trading are effectively running a monopoly now. {actually "goyou product" but I've no clue what to make of it, in fact it's just another financial company helping people settle their checks so I'm X2 lost; would assume goyo are their rivals and are a lot more successful ones at that}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.44,0:07:28.94,Default,,0,0,0,,This is our chance to snatch Showa \Nfrom under their noses! {to eat into; to encroach; to make inroads; to penetrate (e.g. a market); to break into (e.g. first place); to erode; to cut into (e.g. time, savings)}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.94,0:07:32.82,Default,,0,0,0,,In here, I have everything pertaining \NHayate's local production, documented and arranged.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.82,0:07:36.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Consulting this notebook, \Nshould sate their curiosity to a sufficient extent.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:38.45,0:07:42.43,Sign,,0,0,0,,Kyoto
Dialogue: 0,0:07:42.43,0:07:44.70,Default,,0,0,0,,It all turned out exactly according to my calculations.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.71,0:07:50.72,Sign,,0,0,0,,Soichiro Funaoka, Professor at the Institute of Economic Research, \NUniversity of Kyoto. (Sawako's mentor)
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.71,0:07:50.72,Default,,0,0,100,,If the self-restrictions are imposed, \Nthe Japanese cars will rise in price by an average of $2,000.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.72,0:07:55.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Thus, even if the exports fall, that increase in price \Nwould be enough to cover our losses.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.04,0:07:56.97,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we might even end up profiting from this. {I hope he means this by "no, even a change(for a purchase) may come"}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.97,0:08:00.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, the American car makers \Nwould also jump on the bandwagon, increasing prices.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.40,0:08:04.23,Default,,0,0,0,,In the end, it's the ordinary American customers \Nwho would suffer the most losses?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.23,0:08:05.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, more or less so.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.83,0:08:08.90,Default,,0,0,0,,It'll become a textbook example \Nof a joint U.S.-Japan cartel.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:08.90,0:08:11.49,Default,,0,0,0,,But I shouldn't think it'll be a lasting enterprise. {/But I don't see that lasting for long.}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.49,0:08:12.99,Default,,0,0,0,,What do you mean by that?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.99,0:08:14.49,Default,,0,0,0,,The exchange rates... {hope he means this}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.49,0:08:19.20,Default,,0,0,70,,After 1970, the American foreign trade balance \Nturned into a deficit.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.49,0:08:23.50,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\frz270.6\move(616,431,616,19,3007,7469)\c&HE8F4EB&\blur0.4\bord0}Surplus      Deficit
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.49,0:08:18.31,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fscx86\fscy93\move(305,55,306.4,-18.4,3087,3874)\blur0.4\bord0\c&HE8F4EB&}Japan-USA Foreign Trade Profitability Chart           \h
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.49,0:08:21.39,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\frz271.1\fscx99\fscy82\move(571.555,291.556,570.666,-90.444,3007,6885)\blur0.4\bord0\c&HE8F4EB&} Blue chart - Japan
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.49,0:08:18.16,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fscx85\fscy106\move(83.556,9.778,77.333,-42.666,3087,3632)\blur0.4\bord0\c&HE8F4EB&}Billions of dollars
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.08,0:08:23.50,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fscx95\fscy98\frz270.9\move(383.112,565.334,384.89,298.667,1,2788)\blur0.4\bord0\c&HE8F4EB&}Red chart - USA
Dialogue: 1,0:08:19.20,0:08:23.50,Default,,0,0,83,,Since then, with every year passing, \Nthe deficit had been deepening. {lit: width was increasing}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.07,0:08:23.50,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\move(46,470,46,395,13,839)\blur0.4\bord0\c&HE8F4EB&}Year
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.23,0:08:23.50,Title card,,0,0,0,,{\blur0.4\bord10\move(323.556,488.556,324.444,426,24,640)\3c&H291810&\c&HE8F4EB&} (Note) Vertical axis is represented by a logarithmic function \N{\fs19} (Source) Nomura Research Institute "Business World Observation May 1984" {(注)縦軸は対数\N(出所)野村総合研究所「財界観測 1984.5」}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.50,0:08:27.29,Default,,0,0,0,,At the same time, the budget deficit \Nhad also been worsening.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.29,0:08:30.65,Default,,0,0,0,,So to fill this void somehow, \Nthey relied on loans from other countries.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.65,0:08:33.95,Default,,0,0,0,,But as you well know, \Na loan is something you pay back with an interest.{added} {lit: you can't go not returning it}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.95,0:08:34.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.49,0:08:37.52,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, the American foreign debt \Ncannot be paid back now,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.52,0:08:42.13,Default,,0,0,0,,without printing out dollars, the world's currency \Nin ridiculous amounts so as to cover the interest rates.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:42.13,0:08:44.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I.e. we'll see an outflow of dollars. {outflow (of people, capital, etc.); drain (of gold, talent, etc. from a country); leak (e.g. of personal information)}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.06,0:08:47.02,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, the dollar would depreciate,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.02,0:08:49.48,Default,,0,0,0,,entailing a major shift in the exchange rates.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.48,0:08:51.57,Default,,0,0,0,,With yen strengthening against the dollar?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.57,0:08:56.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Correct. One dollar, currently traded for about 200 yen, \Nwill then drop to under 170 yen if not less.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.28,0:08:58.37,Default,,0,0,0,,And the decline might not end there.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.37,0:09:00.02,Default,,0,0,0,,But if that turns out to be the case,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:00.02,0:09:03.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan would be in favor \Nof switching to local production in the U.S., right? {I don't see how one leads to another but literally, she says "coerced into", although if we switch out coerced to "in favor of" it makes perftct sense so I'll do it}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.31,0:09:05.79,Default,,0,0,0,,That's what I'm getting at.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.79,0:09:07.88,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, the main issue becomes...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.88,0:09:10.09,Default,,0,0,0,,The surge{/deterioration} of domestic unemployment?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.09,0:09:13.88,Default,,0,0,0,,The subcontractors are probably going \Nto be hit the hardest by that change. {/sustaing the biggest damage}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:22.61,0:09:26.87,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're doing this research for Showa, \Nyou might be interested in records on subcontractors, right? {unsure why he says "if you investigate showa" and not "for showa"; also the whole sentence is elusive to me: if you ..., I wonder if there's also any materials/records on ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.87,0:09:27.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.88,0:09:29.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Archives department chief, Yuki.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.27,0:09:30.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah, I apologize...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.90,0:09:33.89,Default,,0,0,0,,I never stopped by to sell hello \Nand just helped myself to it...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.89,0:09:35.90,Default,,0,0,0,,I work in Business Headquarters...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.90,0:09:37.91,Default,,0,0,0,,Matsumoto Sawako, isn't that right?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:37.91,0:09:38.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.13,0:09:41.24,Default,,0,0,0,,You've already been introduced to me via a proxy. {lit: from her, I've heard rumors about you}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.24,0:09:42.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Yukie...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.16,0:09:47.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, I always come here when I need a break. {taking a breather; relaxation; vent hole}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.17,0:09:47.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:48.42,0:09:54.40,Default,,0,0,0,,In the late 70s, I also had the experience of dealing with \Nfrictions, pertaining the foreign trade of color TVs.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.40,0:09:57.20,Default,,0,0,0,,We'll be in dire straits, \Nif we switch to local car production, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:57.70,0:09:58.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:58.65,0:10:02.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Actually, if that helps, would you like me \Nto get you the records on color TVs local production?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.93,0:10:04.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Those would be of great service to me!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.68,0:10:06.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, where was it...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.60,0:10:10.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Yukie, what kind of person Yuki is, exactly?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:10.43,0:10:13.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The guy who's a thousand times as sharp as our Manager. {kirete could be man of ability so i'm working from under this, although not sure as I don't see how it can be comparative since she says "zutto"}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:13.13,0:10:16.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Although people said he had \Na bright future waiting for him, {having great hopes for (someone's future); expecting much of; pinning one's hopes on}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:16.20,0:10:18.99,Default,,0,0,0,,it seems, he had to take the blame \Nfor something unfortunate
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.99,0:10:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,and was made into a window-starer, \Nremoved from the line of promotion. {I absolutely hate this and I don't know how to make this line sensible in english, while keeping "window" in it and keeping CPS under 20 because obviously we see the window now for a reason; madogiwazoku is "useless employees (shunted off by a window to pass their remaining time until retirement)" or in a broader sense: "\NA term used to ridicule a middle-aged or older office worker who has left the career line and has a sloppy job . It is said to have originated from a 1977 Hokkaido Shimbun column in which people who were not given a real job and spent their days reading newspapers at window seats and staring blankly at the outside were called ``madosaki uncle.'' At a time when the lifetime employment system was still deeply rooted in companies, it was considered morally wrong to dismiss an employee who had not made any gross negligence . For this reason, companies did not dismiss or change jobs for middle-aged or older employees hired during the high-growth era, under the pretext of being on standby so that they could work as needed. After the collapse of the bubble economy, companies could not afford to keep window workers, so they actively implemented restructuring to reduce personnel , such as introducing a selective retirement system (early retirement preferential system) for voluntary retirement and paying a higher retirement allowance."; literally "window edge tribe"}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.19,0:10:37.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Two years after the {first }self-restrictions were imposed.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:37.38,0:10:38.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Because the price of Japanese cars rose,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.97,0:10:41.95,Default,,0,0,0,,The American industries have also been able \Nto ramp up the prices.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:41.95,0:10:45.53,Default,,0,0,0,,The performance of the imperiled Central Motor Company \Nalso began to improve.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:45.53,0:10:49.69,Default,,0,0,100,,Then, as the yen rose because of the changes \Nin the American monetary policies,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.98,0:10:52.96,Sign,,0,0,0,,Central Motor Company Shareholders' Meeting {セントラル社 株主総会}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.69,0:10:52.98,Default,,0,0,100,,the price of Japanese cars also rose once again.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.98,0:10:58.53,Default,,0,0,0,,...and so, I'm proud to announce that the unjust \Nyen depreciation{/exchange rates}, low wages, long working hours,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.53,0:11:02.37,Default,,0,0,0,,government protectionism, \Nand other foul means the Japanese used for profiteering
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.37,0:11:04.66,Default,,0,0,0,,were subjected to international criticism.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.66,0:11:08.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Japan was left no choice but to radically alter its ways.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.25,0:11:12.75,Default,,0,0,0,,But above all, the dollar-yen exchange rate \Nis approaching a reasonable level.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:12.75,0:11:15.10,Default,,0,0,0,,It is weakening the competitiveness of Japanese cars.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:15.10,0:11:17.05,Default,,0,0,0,,In time, it will create conditions,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.05,0:11:22.03,Default,,0,0,0,,where their manufacturers have no choice, but to step forth \Nand switch to local production in our country.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:22.03,0:11:26.25,Default,,0,0,0,,If the battle is in the U.S., \Nthe prospect of losing it is nonexistent for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.25,0:11:29.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Furthermore, I expect \Nthat large quantities of our "Central" cars
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.14,0:11:32.77,Default,,0,0,0,,would soon comprise a significant part \Nof our exports to Japan!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.61,0:11:39.09,Default,,0,0,0,,We're not amused!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.09,0:11:43.14,Default,,0,0,130,,Moving the factories to the U.S. \Nwould only result in unemployment!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.09,0:11:44.87,Sign,,0,0,0,,Showa Motor Co. Workers Union President \N Katsutoshi Sato {昭和自動車労働組合長\N佐藤勝利}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.14,0:11:44.87,Default,,0,0,130,,For us, simple workers,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.87,0:11:46.94,Default,,0,0,130,,it's all harm and no gain! {百害あって一利なしである!} {page 23 of volume 1 btw}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.94,0:11:50.12,Default,,0,0,0,,Be firm in your opposition, \Nfor the sake of our union's survival!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.87,0:11:52.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't let them steal our jobs! {職を奪うな}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.37,0:11:55.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Not in a thousand years, \Nwe'll be the martyrs to the trade frictions! {fall victim }
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.92,0:11:57.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't that right, gentlemen?!
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.72,0:12:04.55,Default,,0,0,0,,At the board meeting this morning,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:04.55,0:12:09.25,Default,,0,0,0,,our company had made a decision \Ntowards switching to local production in the U.S.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:09.25,0:12:12.17,Default,,0,0,130,,Therefore, we ask you, \NGoyo and Taihei representatives,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:09.25,0:12:11.27,Sign,,0,0,0,,Goyo Trading{/bussan - actually, they're kinda financial operators like taihei so "manufacturing/product" seems out of place here but we'll see what they're up to in next episodes} Business Headquarters \N General Manager Gondo                   Kunio Tsugawa
Dialogue: 0,0:12:12.17,0:12:15.92,Default,,0,0,0,,to come up with an optimal strategy \Nfor organizing our local production. {/how should we arrange ... so it'll go well?}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:15.92,0:12:18.03,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd like you to consider all the possibilities.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.03,0:12:20.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Huh. Must be you're trying to make fun of us. {/goyo} {to look down on (someone); to make fun of; to put down; to treat with contempt; to underestimate​}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.75,0:12:24.77,Default,,0,0,0,,What the interest in competition, \Nwhen your opponent is a softie girl fresh out of school?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:25.28,0:12:27.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Tsugawa, please watch your language.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.70,0:12:28.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:28.41,0:12:31.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Toda, we hope you don't go too hard on us this time. {not sure what to make of hitotsu here} {[Formal] To treat someone gently and kindly. In the form of ``Ote Yawarakuni'', it is used as a greeting when starting a game. "Please be gentle with me."\N\N("Digital Daijisen")\N\N"Ote softly" means to reduce the degree of severity, and is mainly used as a greeting before conflicts such as sports.\N\NSince it contains the nuance of "I am weaker than you, please take it easy" , it is also used to admit that the other person is stronger than you, or to show humility. - really fucking struggling to get the meaning across in english, it's really just a general expression of humility}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.51,0:12:33.76,Default,,0,0,0,,No, we're the ones hoping you don't go too hard.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.76,0:12:36.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you mind if I ask just one thing?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.36,0:12:37.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Please do.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:37.41,0:12:40.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Labor unions problem, \Nwhat do you intend to do about them?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:40.30,0:12:44.62,Default,,0,0,0,,You can trust us to deal with that issue \Nand devote yourself fully to developing the strategy. {/do investigation without minding it}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.55,0:12:50.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Goyo's Gondo is the one with the bitter record \Nof repetitively making fun of us. {really not sure - it seems "to lick/taste the bitterness" is independent phrase, but I want to believe it's connected to waht kunio said about matsumoto because it's the same word}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.52,0:12:53.60,Default,,0,0,0,,This time, we must do our utmost to best those guys. {to outwit; to get the better of; to leave (an opponent) dumbfounded; to expose (someone's) nose}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:53.60,0:12:56.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Department chief, please trust me to deal with this.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:56.50,0:12:58.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Anticipating this kind of a scenario -
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.38,0:13:02.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Hayate consulting us about factory relocation, \NI had already secretly drawn up a strategy!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.51,0:13:04.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, that's pretty handy.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.51,0:13:07.53,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll present them with a revolutionary idea \Nof taking over local plants. {hope "in one's own way or style​" here means "something noone else would come up with"; lit: proposal of inheriting}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.53,0:13:10.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Just let me draw up a report, \Nyou'll see everything yourself!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.58,0:13:14.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Sounds good. Matsumoto, \Nwhat's your plan on dealing with this assignment?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:14.92,0:13:18.39,Default,,0,0,0,,I thought I'd start with a research \Non subcontractors' situation.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.39,0:13:19.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Subcontractors?
Dialogue: 0,0:13:19.55,0:13:22.30,Default,,0,0,0,,What use you think will come out of it \Nat this stage? {I think he means "so late into the affair/when the situation is clear already"}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:22.30,0:13:26.71,Default,,0,0,0,,If you have nothing better to do with your time, \Nyou should rather come help with my work!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:26.71,0:13:28.93,Default,,0,0,0,,With all due respect to your idea,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:28.93,0:13:33.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Goyo Division are likely to have already made \Nnecessary arrangements regarding potential candidates. {could be "to come to an agreement (in bargaining, etc.); to strike a bargain" or "to take (preventive) measures"}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.54,0:13:35.77,Default,,0,0,0,,But if we take a non-standard approach now, {/from different angle}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.77,0:13:38.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Showa would be more inclined \Nto favor us in the future. {lit: in a way like we'll have relationship with showa in future}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.97,0:13:41.07,Default,,0,0,0,,I believe, it's the only way to ensure that.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.82,0:13:46.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Indeed, we also have to deal with the pressing issue \Nof deciding how to dispose of parts subcontractors. {/what should ... do}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:46.63,0:13:50.04,Default,,0,0,0,,I got it. I want you to also draw up a report \Nin the nearest time.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:50.49,0:13:51.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.54,0:13:53.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Use as much money as you need. {金に糸目はつけん}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.04,0:13:54.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't be picky with methods. {/by any means, fair or foul}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.75,0:13:57.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Just see to it that our cover isn't broken. {could be both literal: "to break; to be smashed a person's back" and something like "backing; support; backer; supporter doesn't to come to light; to become clear; to be identified; to be revealed"; ただバックがワレるのだけは困る - volume 1 page 28; it's "I'm only worried about our cover being broken." in TL so I'm sticking with that too}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.04,0:13:59.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Make every possible precaution about that.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.25,0:14:00.67,Default,,0,0,0,,I know that much.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:01.17,0:14:04.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Tsugawa, we two have quite the history \Nof doing business together. {lit: my connectiong to ... is not a shallow friendship}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.30,0:14:09.49,Default,,0,0,0,,With only union backing him, Sato already has the ambitions \Nto run for the upper house of the Diet. {佐藤には労組を後ろ盾に参院選に打って出ようという野望もあ}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.49,0:14:13.31,Default,,0,0,0,,We just need to get hold of a good scandal about him. \NOr fabricate one.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.72,0:14:17.06,Default,,0,0,0,,Whoa, whoa, now it's really heating up, isn't it? {/this time }
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.06,0:14:17.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.07,0:14:22.72,Default,,0,0,0,,After building up our trust with Showa for all that time, \Nno way I give them up to the likes of Taihei. {/relationship}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:23.82,0:14:27.74,Default,,0,0,0,,Ever since the self-restrictions were placed, \Nthe plant had not expanded an inch. {lit: the growth of production stopped}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.74,0:14:29.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And our future prospects are also less than bright.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.97,0:14:31.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Because of the strengthening yen, right? {/it's hard/diffcult/painful}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:33.06,0:14:36.99,Default,,0,0,0,,After everything Showa have done for us, \Nspeaking ill of them is the last thing I'd wanna do...
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.99,0:14:39.64,Default,,0,0,0,,But we always end up being the ones to feel the crunch. {lit: ill effects; negative consequences; burden; strain; brunt; loss comes here}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.64,0:14:41.03,Default,,0,0,0,,That may very well be true.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.03,0:14:45.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Currently, Showa are seriously considering \Nswitching to local production in the U.S.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:45.59,0:14:47.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah... What was it just now?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.59,0:14:48.84,Default,,0,0,0,,You can't be serious!
Dialogue: 0,0:14:48.84,0:14:52.57,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm told the Showa's labor union \Nis vehemently opposed to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.57,0:14:54.10,Default,,0,0,0,,And now they're readily accepting it? {at a moment's notice; readily}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.10,0:14:57.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes... It appears so, for the moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.10,0:15:03.01,Default,,0,0,0,,But then, even if they build the assembly line over there, \Nwhat would they put on it, without the Japan-made parts?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:03.01,0:15:07.36,Default,,0,0,0,,It's us, the small subcontractors, \Nwho make the Japanese cars so great and affordable! {/thanks to ... said to be superior}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.36,0:15:11.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Do you suppose they'll make us \Nsend the parts there all the way from Japan?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:11.37,0:15:13.15,Default,,0,0,0,,That would've been reasonable, but...
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.15,0:15:17.87,Default,,0,0,0,,They're about to reinstate a law that says, \Nunless over 50% of the car,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:17.87,0:15:21.40,Default,,0,0,0,,including parts, is made locally, \Nit's still considered an import.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.83,0:15:22.88,Default,,0,0,0,,But if that happens...
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.88,0:15:26.38,Default,,0,0,0,,What do they suppose will become \Nof little companies like mine?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.01,0:15:30.99,Default,,0,0,0,,It can't be... I'm obviously too old to immigrate now!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:35.60,0:15:38.97,Default,,0,0,0,,Matsumoto, for the subcontractors, \Nthis is a matter of life and death!
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.97,0:15:43.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Isn't it within Taihei's power to create some new job for us?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.61,0:15:46.61,Default,,0,0,0,,A new work for car parts manufacturers...
Dialogue: 0,0:15:48.86,0:15:51.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Taking over a poorly managed local company?
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.95,0:15:53.99,Default,,0,0,0,,That's a gutsy plan, if I do say so myself.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.99,0:15:58.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Mikawa, if we choose your approach, \Nthis job would call for some sharp practice. {/we'll be able to restart the work right away.} {to regain one's strength; to recover one's spirit; to be invigorated; to be encouraged} {was "we'll have a pretty lively business" in TL} {unsure, could very well be "it'll become a brute work/sharp practice"... actually, considering what he says next, let's ball with it.}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:58.20,0:16:01.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Without going that far, \Nwe'll never be able to win Showa over!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.46,0:16:04.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Especially if it results in a cheapest plan of all!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.71,0:16:06.09,Default,,0,0,0,,That may well be true,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.09,0:16:09.21,Default,,0,0,0,,but it also means \Na huge initial investment would be required.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:09.21,0:16:14.34,Default,,0,0,0,,If Showa fall short of the investments required, \Nour company could look after them with our own funds. {very unsure what he means, lit: I think our company should take care of any shortfalls in Showa's financial resources.; I suspect "our company would bail them out/loan them" which makes just as much sense with the next line as "our company would take over from them"; it was surprisingly neither in TL}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.34,0:16:16.94,Default,,0,0,0,,And then, our company could also use it \Nto do business there. {lit: That's where we can do business with people. - no clue what financial coucilors would do with a factory or what business with people they're planning to do there, if prev line meant "we'll loan them" then this would be "how we do deals with people" but again, why people, like single humans? I'm suspecting "would profit from this too (interest etc)"}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.68,0:16:19.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Boy, are you meticulous. {shrewd; astute; cunning; alert​ - here it means someone who doesn't forget anything}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.98,0:16:22.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Alright, fly to U.S. immediately \Nand secure the property for us. {TLC, no idea what's this atatte/watatte, not in manga either}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.52,0:16:23.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Got it!
Dialogue: 0,0:16:24.61,0:16:26.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Matsumoto, you got something to offer too?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:26.98,0:16:31.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. I was curious: \Nonce Showa relocate their production to the U.S.,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:31.09,0:16:33.13,Default,,0,0,0,,how would they supply the car parts there?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.13,0:16:37.23,Default,,0,0,0,,In particular, my research was focused \Non how would subcontractors weather that storm.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.23,0:16:39.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So, what were your conclusions?
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.75,0:16:43.25,Default,,0,0,0,,A few years ago, we had similar trade frictions over color TVs.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.25,0:16:47.25,Default,,0,0,0,,During those, the Japanese manufacturers \Nwere also unanimously switching to local production. {to take the plunge; to decide; to embark on; to venture into; to launch out into / all; all together; unanimously​}
Dialogue: 0,0:16:47.25,0:16:52.26,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result, the export of color TVs to the U.S. \Nis now virtually nonexistent.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:52.26,0:16:56.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Electrical appliance manufacturers \Nmoved everything abroad, including their parts divisions.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.58,0:17:01.77,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the subcontractors that were left behind \Nstill made it through with little trouble.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:01.77,0:17:02.77,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:02.77,0:17:06.58,Default,,0,0,0,,But that was because the lines \Nthat were previously making TVs for the U.S.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.58,0:17:10.50,Default,,0,0,0,,could be effortlessly converted to VTR production lines.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.50,0:17:15.01,Default,,0,0,0,,In the form of VTRs, \Na terrific pinch hitter had entered the field. {considering TL note here to explain the pinch hitter comes out at a time of crisis to replace the injured player}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:15.01,0:17:18.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you saying that no such pinch hitter \Ncan appear in the automobile industry?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:18.99,0:17:23.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactly. Cars use considerably more parts than TVs.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.75,0:17:29.25,Default,,0,0,0,,The numerous subcontractors also vary in size and obviously enough, cannot all follow the parent company abroad.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:30.11,0:17:33.97,Default,,0,0,0,,You were proactively urging Hayate \Nto commit to the local production.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:33.97,0:17:36.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Yet for Showa, you're skeptical about it... {denial; negation; repudiation; disavowal​}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.76,0:17:41.50,Default,,0,0,0,,By then, Hayate had much fewer subcontractors, \Nso they didn't run into a lot of trouble settling this. {arranged; taken care of; settled; completed; finished - sounds weird if we don't specify how they settled it - did they find new ones locally? did they move old ones with them?}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.50,0:17:42.22,Default,,0,0,0,,I get it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.22,0:17:45.02,Default,,0,0,0,,But then, have you any solution \Nfor cutting this Gordian Knot? {lit: answer the plan to overcome an obstacle or break out of a deadlock; breakthrough solution}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:45.02,0:17:49.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. Together with Yukie \Nand the archives department chief Yuki,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.31,0:17:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,we can draw up a new business plan, \Nthat'd facilitate a closer cooperation with the subcontractors. {I have no idea what she means, lit is "plan that can be subcontracted" but I don't see for the life of it how it can solve the issue of moving them to us??? later on the meeting they also just say "a proposal on dealing with ..." and it's eventually rejected anyway so doesn't matter I guess...; not in manga either}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.53,0:17:55.75,Default,,0,0,0,,I see. Please do that as soon as possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:55.75,0:17:56.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.41,0:18:14.52,Default,,0,0,0,,A takeover of a local enterprise? I see. \NSounds very much like our Manager Mikawa.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.42,0:18:19.93,Default,,0,0,0,,But hey, stealthily buying out someone else's company... \NIsn't it too high-handed? {overbearing; coercive; pushy; forcible; high-handed}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:19.93,0:18:23.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Especially when you have no idea \Nhow people working there would feel about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.93,0:18:27.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Chairman Sato!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.94,0:18:31.94,Default,,0,0,0,,After opposing it so vehemently, \Nhow come you suddenly changed your stance?!
Dialogue: 0,0:18:32.44,0:18:37.41,Default,,0,0,0,,How do we explain this to the union members, who've always \Nbeen believing the management unquestionably?! {}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.41,0:18:40.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, I thought I explained this point to you \Nmultiple times already.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:40.95,0:18:46.19,Default,,0,0,0,,Not even a trade union can exist in isolation \Nfrom the international economic environment.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.19,0:18:49.70,Default,,0,0,0,,What the... Don't tell me \Nyou've made a shadow deal with the company! {no clue what's "bid rigging; collusion (on contract bidding); (illegal) price-fixing agreement/consultation" here; was "you talked to ..." in TL}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:50.33,0:18:53.70,Default,,0,0,0,,How rude! One should know \Nwhat he can say and what he can't.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.38,0:19:01.79,Default,,0,0,0,,I think you'd be quite amused to see what's inside here.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:02.21,0:19:03.35,Default,,0,0,0,,What could it be?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.79,0:19:06.23,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(150,0)} Showa Motor Union chairman: {The }spicy {and colorful }story{ of money, lust and abuse of authority}! {too lazy to ocr tbh, believing 2020 me}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.94,0:19:07.98,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a sham! {fabrication; made-up story; sham; hoax; put-up job; frame-up; trumped-up charge}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:07.98,0:19:10.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Too bad I couldn't care less whether or not it is.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:10.81,0:19:15.73,Default,,0,0,0,,But I bet a great many people would like  \Nto see this jolly kind of article in the evening news. {added}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:15.73,0:19:20.61,Default,,0,0,0,,After all, it's a scandal, concerning a big shot labor union chairman, aiming to run for the upper house of the Diet.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.61,0:19:23.23,Default,,0,0,0,,How is that not an attention grabber? {unsure what he means: It's a great bait, don't you think?; bait; lure; enticement}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:25.08,0:19:29.96,Default,,0,0,0,,With all due respect to the Taihei company efforts, \Nit has been decided that the production lines expansion
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.96,0:19:33.21,Default,,0,0,0,,would be conducted according to the plan \Nproposed by Goyo side, this time.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.21,0:19:34.34,Default,,0,0,0,,What did you say?!
Dialogue: 0,0:19:34.96,0:19:38.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you saying our plan was in some way deficient?{/flawed}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:38.09,0:19:40.32,Default,,0,0,0,,No, it wasn't exactly deficient. It's just...
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.32,0:19:41.84,Default,,0,0,0,,"Just" what?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.84,0:19:45.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Both proposals involved a takeover of a local enterprise.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.60,0:19:49.50,Default,,0,0,0,,They were similar to the point where both \Nchose North Carolina as a destination.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:50.35,0:19:52.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Goyo chose a takeover, too?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:52.09,0:19:54.36,Default,,0,0,0,,The key difference was in the cost.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.36,0:19:58.44,Default,,0,0,0,,On the Goyo side, it was an agricultural equipment \Nmanufacturer about to go bankrupt.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:58.44,0:19:59.44,Default,,0,0,0,,What...
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.44,0:20:04.37,Default,,0,0,0,,So the Japanese company \Nthat bought up this manufacturer's shares had been Goyo?! {buying up of goods; cornering (market) / stock; share}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:04.37,0:20:05.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Did it in the nick of time. {very small difference (esp. in time); tiny interval}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.85,0:20:08.41,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, regarding the alternative proposal...
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.41,0:20:11.35,Default,,0,0,0,,The Subcontractors Strategy, \Ndeveloped by Taihei's Matsumoto {again, just "matter/case/instance of sub..." but no details about what it actuall is}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:11.35,0:20:14.63,Default,,0,0,0,,was also deemed highly novel by our company's board.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.63,0:20:19.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, we hope for a productive future cooperation \Nwith Taihei and their out-of-the-box analysis. {forward-looking; positive; constructive​ study/investigation}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.87,0:20:22.89,Default,,0,0,0,,If you say it's so out-of-the-box, \Nyou should start acting upon it ASAP. {TLC, no clue what she means: without saying "forward-looking; positive; constructive​", please do immediately}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:22.89,0:20:28.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Matsumoto, having helped myself to reading your report, \NI'd like to subscribe to every word he said.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:28.64,0:20:30.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Showa are usually rather slow on the uptake, {slowly; inefficiently; tardily; dawdling​}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:30.81,0:20:32.92,Default,,0,0,0,,so I'd rather have you working for us.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.65,0:20:36.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Gondo! We'd be in trouble if that happens.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.17,0:20:39.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh, it was just a "what if" soliloquy.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:39.18,0:20:40.69,Default,,0,0,0,,It was a bit hard to tell... {TLC, no clue what he means, maybe "I was confused"}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.74,0:20:44.20,Default,,0,0,130,,I hear the company's new owners are Japanese.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.40,0:20:45.91,Sign,,0,0,0,,North Carolina, USA
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.20,0:20:49.16,Default,,0,0,130,,They're going to turn this into an assembly plant \Nfor Japanese cars. And they're going to keep us on. {/employ/hire}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:49.16,0:20:53.25,Default,,0,0,0,,I'd salute this new owner even if he's a monkey, \Nas long as I don't get laid off. {welcome; reception}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:53.25,0:20:57.15,Default,,0,0,0,,But I've heard that workers in Japan \Nare treated like slaves.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:57.15,0:20:59.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Aren't we all corporate slaves? {/company's}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:59.17,0:21:02.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, if worse comes to worst, \Nwe can appeal to the union. They'll do something about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:02.83,0:21:05.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Every time we rely on them, \Nwe end up paying even more! {/asking them is always expensive}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:05.18,0:21:09.16,Default,,0,0,0,,At any rate, we should let the Japanese know \Nthat things won't be all that simple.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:14.32,0:21:19.71,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a shame Department Chief and Manager got overlooked, \Nbut at least we know our efforts bore some definite fruits. {fruits (of one's labors); gain; result; returns}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.71,0:21:22.34,Default,,0,0,0,,Sawako, let's have a big party tonight! {no clue what she means by "let's make grand; magnificent; lavish; large scale; prosperous; thriving; lively"} {page 59 of volume 1}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:23.32,0:21:25.78,Default,,0,0,0,,Yukie, nothing wrong with having a big party,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.78,0:21:28.58,Default,,0,0,0,,but really, this is a watershed moment \Nboth for us and for the Goyo guys. {critical moment; do-or-die situation; critical juncture - no fucking clue how this is so for any of them}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.58,0:21:29.87,Default,,0,0,0,,For Goyo too?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:29.87,0:21:31.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Right. Even after they get the factory going,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.75,0:21:36.27,Default,,0,0,0,,they'll only be able to talk about success when the cars \Nthey make are no inferior to those assembled in Japan. {/no different}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:36.27,0:21:38.59,Default,,0,0,0,,In the end, isn't it wonderful, {added}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.59,0:21:42.63,Default,,0,0,0,,when people of different backgrounds{/lifestyles}, \Nlanguages, and skin colors work on them side by side?
Dialogue: 0,0:21:42.63,0:21:43.88,Default,,0,0,0,,I guess so...
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.88,0:21:49.11,Default,,0,0,0,,However, a few years from now, when every single Japanese manufacturer switches to local production model,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:49.11,0:21:52.74,Default,,0,0,0,,there'll surely come a time when supply exceeds demand \Nand a surplus of cars will form.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.74,0:21:53.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Sawako,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.20,0:21:57.40,Default,,0,0,0,,I have a strong feeling \Nit'll be your turn to act once again.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:57.40,0:22:02.40,Default,,0,0,0,,I pray that your business style, born from considerateness, \Nremains forever this way! {lit is "coming/passing thru heart" but I think he means this; also I hate this word but can't come up with anything better}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.87,0:22:12.48,Default,,0,0,0,,IMF - The International Monetary Fund
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.48,0:22:17.47,Default,,0,0,0,,evaluated the consequences of the restrictions, \Nplaced from 1981 to 1984 on exports from Japan to the U.S.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:17.47,0:22:21.53,Default,,0,0,0,,A detailed summary of the damage incurred \Nby ordinary American consumers is as follows:
Dialogue: 0,0:22:22.48,0:22:27.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Over these four years, the prices of all new \NAmerican-made cars rose by an average of 50%.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.34,0:22:33.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Had export self-restrictions not been placed, \Nthey place the expected increase in price to just 27%.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.52,0:22:40.34,Default,,0,0,0,,As a result of this, the combined amount of money \Noverpaid by the consumers was over $17 billion.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:40.90,0:22:44.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Converted to yen at the exchange rate of that period, \Nit's about 4 trillion yen.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.79,0:22:48.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Which makes it a trillion yen yearly.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:51.19,0:22:54.15,Sign,,0,0,0,,In the next episode
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.36,0:22:57.92,Default,,0,0,0,,The amount of money being traded on currency market \Nannually is $400 trillion.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:57.92,0:22:59.92,Default,,0,0,0,,With the yen rate violently fluctuating,
Dialogue: 0,0:22:59.92,0:23:02.38,Default,,0,0,0,,the eyes of the exchange dealers are glued to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.38,0:23:06.57,Default,,0,0,0,,Newly put in charge of the Exchange Consulting Subdivision, \NMatsumoto Sawako
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.57,0:23:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,is also closely observing the corrections of the price. {no clue what's the fist word or what is she observing}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:09.04,0:23:14.68,Default,,0,0,0,,Next time in the Introduction to Japanese Economics: \NExchange Game. Don't miss it.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.28,0:23:16.18,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 2\NExchange Game {為替ゲーム}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:26.24,0:23:29.53,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Driving down the midnight highway {真夜中の Highway}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.49,0:23:33.93,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Crossing through my memories {横切ってゆく Memories}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:34.70,0:23:37.89,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Just tonight, I ask you to be silent {ただ黙ったままあの日}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.18,0:23:41.92,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Eye to eye, we stare at each other {Eye と Eye 見つめてた}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:43.48,0:23:46.63,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Some nostalgic love song {懐かしい Love song}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.46,0:23:50.34,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Slowly flowing out from the radio {流れた From the radio}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:51.86,0:23:55.43,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,It's like fighting back {閉じこめた悲しみを　叩くように}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:55.43,0:24:02.02,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,this sadness, that's been locked away for long
Dialogue: 0,0:24:02.02,0:24:04.48,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Oh baby play for me!
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.48,0:24:08.54,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Soul music \NSweet soul music
Dialogue: 0,0:24:08.54,0:24:12.47,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,It's suffocating, let me hear it {せつなく聞かせて}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.47,0:24:16.99,Default,ED Trans,0,0,0,,Sweet soul music \NI love you!
